---
<Base
  title="About | Alfred Williamson"
  description="About Alfred Williamson: applied mathematics at Harvard College, game theory and geopolitics, research on Russia–China relations, and public advocacy for international students."
  ogType="profile"
  current="about"
>
  <h1>About</h1>
  <p>
    I am a second-year student at Harvard College studying applied mathematics. My
    current work sits at the intersection of game theory and geopolitics: how formal
    models of cooperation and defection hold up when the players are states with
    asymmetric power, asymmetric information, and choices that are never simply
    binary. I expect this to become my senior thesis.
  </p>
  <p>
    I am a research intern at the Regional Institute of Security Studies (RISS),
    where I analyse Russia&rsquo;s economic relationship with China through customs
    data, with policy analysis produced through RISS&rsquo;s partnership with the
    Royal United Services Institute. At Harvard I am Deputy Chair of the Institute
    of Politics&rsquo; Global Affairs Program, where I lead a fifty-person team, the
    undergraduate body&rsquo;s first International Student Liaison, and Head of Growth
    &amp; Strategy at the Harvard International Review. I also co-founded Varsko
    Intelligence, an early-stage project on geopolitical risk.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before this I was a guest researcher at the University of Copenhagen&rsquo;s
    Faculty of Law, coding decisions of the African Court on Human and Peoples&rsquo;
    Rights at its centre for international courts, and researched military
    applications of synthetic biology for NATO&rsquo;s innovation division with the
    Harvard Undergraduate Foreign Policy Initiative, presenting the findings at NATO
    headquarters in Brussels. I co-founded Advisor AI, an assistant for financial
    advisors, during my first year.
  </p>
  <p>
    In 2025, when the federal government moved to restrict Harvard&rsquo;s international
    students, I spoke publicly against the university yielding &mdash; at rallies covered by
    the <a href="https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2025/9/7/students-for-freedom-fall-protest/">Harvard Crimson</a>,
    on <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2025/05/30/us/video/harvard-international-students-visa-trump-digvid">CNN</a>,
    by <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/welsh-harvard-student-caught-up-trump-row-fears-he-may-never-return-2025-05-28/">Reuters</a>,
    and on <a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/06/16/nx-s1-5432750/harvard-lawsuit-international-students-hearing">NPR</a>;
    the full list is on the <a href="/press/">press page</a>. I remain involved in that work.
  </p>
  <p>
    I grew up in Cardiff, half Welsh and half Danish, which is one reason the
    politics of small states next to large ones holds my attention. I rowed for
    Wales, and was part of the UK team that won the NASA Space Settlement Design
    Competition. I speak English and Danish, some Norwegian, and am slowly acquiring
    Spanish. Off duty: piano, saxophone, and long-distance trekking.
  </p>
  <p>
    The best way to reach me is email (footer of this page), or
    <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/alfred-williamson-137b6020b/">LinkedIn</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>For journalists</h2>
  <p class="note">
    Alfred Williamson is a second-year undergraduate at Harvard College studying
    applied mathematics, with research interests in game theory and geopolitics. A
    Welsh-Danish international student, he has been a prominent student voice on US
    visa restrictions affecting international students, appearing on CNN and NPR and
    in coverage by Reuters, the Boston Globe, Newsweek, and the Harvard Crimson. He
    can be reached by email at the address in the footer of alfredwilliamson.com.
  </p>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={jsonLd} />
</Base>
